<p><b>William Gormaly Ball</b> (29 April 1931 – 30 July 1991) was an American stage director and founder of the <a href="American_Conservatory_Theatre" title="American Conservatory Theatre" class="mw-redirect">American Conservatory Theatre</a> (ACT). He was awarded the Drama Desk Vernon Rice Award in 1959 for his production of <a href="Anton_Chekhov" title="Anton Chekhov">Chekhov's</a> <i><a href="Ivanov_(play)" title="Ivanov (play)">Ivanov</a></i> and was nominated for a <a href="Tony_Award" title="Tony Award">Tony Award</a> in 1965 for his production of <a href="Moli%C3%A8re" title="Molière">Molière</a>'s <i><a href="Tartuffe" title="Tartuffe">Tartuffe</a></i>, starring <a href="Michael_O'Sullivan_(actor)" title="Michael O'Sullivan (actor)">Michael O'Sullivan</a> and <a href="Rene_Auberjonois" title="Rene Auberjonois" class="mw-redirect">Rene Auberjonois</a>. He was also a noted director of opera.</p>
